Covariance and Correlation

March 29, 2020

Section 4.7

Covariance

Definition.

Let \( X \) and \( Y \) be random variables with means \( \mu_X \) and \( \mu_Y \). Then the covariance between \( X \) and \( Y \) is

\[ Cov[X,Y] = E[(X-\mu_X)(Y-\mu_Y)] \]

Note.

This is a statistic for measuring the extend of linear association between two random variables.

Result 1.

\[ Cov[X,Y] = E[XY] - \mu_X\mu_Y \]

This is the most commonly used form for covariance. Can you prove this form? How?

Covariance Interpretation

\( X \) and \( Y \) are random variables; covariance asks if we see a linear association between the two draws that occur in an \( (x,y) \) pair.

Consider the function \( f(X,Y) = (X-\mu_X)(Y-\mu_Y) \).

There are four cases to consider, where we are interested in the resulting sign of \( f(X,Y) \).

\[ \small \begin{aligned} \text{I.} \quad X > \mu_X, Y > \mu_Y \quad & \quad \text{II.} \quad X < \mu_X, Y > \mu_Y \\ \text{III.} \quad X < \mu_X, Y < \mu_Y \quad & \quad \text{IV.} \quad X > \mu_X, Y < \mu_Y \\ \end{aligned} \]

Covariance evaluates how likely observations are to be in particular quadrants.

Covariance Interpretation

(A) If we expect to find pairs in I or III, then the random variables have a positive covariance.

  • If a value of \( X \) much larger then \( \mu_X \), we expect that \( Y \) is likely much larger than \( \mu_Y \).

  • If a value of \( X \) much smaller then \( \mu_X \), we expect that \( Y \) is likely much smaller than \( \mu_Y \).

(B) If we expect to find pairs in II or IV, then the random variables have a negative covariance.

  • If a value of \( X \) much larger then \( \mu_X \), we expect that \( Y \) is likely much smaller than \( \mu_Y \).

  • If a value of \( X \) much smaller then \( \mu_X \), we expect that \( Y \) is likely much larger than \( \mu_Y \).

(C ) If we expect to find pairs in all four quadrants, the random variables are not linearly associated.
